  "prompt": "If a rape victim makes a police complaint, is there a publicly accessible record?",
  "response": "When a rape victim makes a police complaint, the specifics of the case, including personal information about the victim, are typically kept confidential to protect the victim's privacy and safety. Although the police may create a record of the complaint, these records are not publicly accessible in the same way as other types of public records. The information is generally kept within law enforcement agencies and, when necessary, shared with other parties involved in the legal process under strict privacy controls.\n\nPublic access might come in the form of anonymized data or aggregated statistics provided by law enforcement agencies, but these will not contain identifiable information about the victim. The goal is to both respect the victim's privacy and ensure the integrity of the investigation and any subsequent legal proceedings.",
